        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>content hub</strong> is a centralized collection of interlinked content around a single core topic — typically one <a href="/glossary/pillar-page/">pillar page</a> surrounded by 10 to 30 supporting articles, all connected through deliberate internal linking. The structure builds topical authority, spreads link equity, and helps Google understand you as the definitive source on that subject.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to 4x (HubSpot)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical size</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1 pillar + 10-30 posts</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Isolated blog posts compete for attention. A hub makes every article stronger by connecting it to a network of related pages. The pillar page catches broad, high-volume searches; supporting articles catch long-tail queries; internal links pass authority in both directions.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a content hub?</h2>
        <p>A content hub is a set of related content pieces organized around one central topic. The centerpiece is a <strong>pillar page</strong> that covers the topic broadly. Supporting articles — cluster content — cover specific subtopics in depth. Every supporting article links back to the pillar, and the pillar links out to each supporting article.</p>
        <p>Think of a textbook. The pillar page is the chapter overview. Supporting articles are the deep-dive sections. Internal links are the table of contents. Together they signal to Google: "we cover this topic thoroughly, from every angle."</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the structure works</div>
          <p>HubSpot research indicates websites using the topic cluster model saw <strong>up to 4x more organic traffic growth</strong> than those publishing isolated posts. Google's algorithm rewards topical depth — a well-built hub competes on authority, not just individual page optimization.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why content hubs matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>Four reasons every serious SEO organizes content into hubs instead of loose blog posts:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Topical authority.</strong> Volume plus structure demonstrates deep expertise. Google rewards sites that cover a topic fully with higher rankings across the whole cluster.</li>
          <li><strong>Better internal linking.</strong> Hubs spread <a href="/glossary/link-equity/">link equity</a> across the site. External backlinks to any one article boost the entire cluster.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher pillar rankings.</strong> Pillar pages inherit authority from supporting articles linking in. Well-built hubs often see the pillar rank for competitive head-terms it could not touch alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Improved user experience.</strong> Readers who land on one article find related depth one click away. Bounce rates drop, time on site rises.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to build a content hub</h2>
        <p>Building a hub is a three-step process: choose the topic, map the subtopics, connect the links.</p>
        <h3>Step 1 — Choose a core topic</h3>
        <p>Pick something broad enough to support 15+ articles but narrow enough that you can genuinely own it. Broad enough: "email marketing." Too broad: "marketing." Too narrow: "email subject line length."</p>
        <h3>Step 2 — Map 10 to 30 subtopics</h3>
        <p>Use <a href="/glossary/keyword-research/">keyword research</a>, <a href="/glossary/people-also-ask-paa/">People Also Ask</a>, and a <a href="/glossary/content-gap-analysis/">content gap analysis</a> to build the subtopic list. Each subtopic must have real search volume and clear intent.</p>
        <h3>Step 3 — Interlink deliberately</h3>
        <p>Every supporting article gets 2 to 3 internal links to related cluster pieces and 1 link back to the pillar. The pillar page links out to every supporting article — usually inline within the relevant section.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of content hubs</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Structure</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Pillar cluster</strong></td><td>1 pillar + 10-30 supporting articles</td><td>SEO topical authority</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Library / resource hub</strong></td><td>Categorized landing pages by content type</td><td>Ungated resource centers</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hub &amp; spoke</strong></td><td>Central hub linking to sub-hubs</td><td>Large multi-topic sites</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Wiki / knowledge base</strong></td><td>Cross-linked reference articles</td><td>Product docs, support</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Glossary / dictionary</strong></td><td>Alphabetical term collection</td><td>Educational reference</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content hub examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Marketing agency — Local SEO hub</h3>
        <p>An agency built a "Local SEO" hub with 25 supporting articles around one pillar page. Within 4 months, the pillar ranked #3 for "local SEO guide" and the cluster drove 8,000+ monthly visits combined.</p>
        <h3>2. Accounting firm — Small business taxes hub</h3>
        <p>An accounting firm created a "Small Business Taxes" hub with 18 supporting articles. The hub generates <strong>3,000 organic visits per month</strong> and produces 40 to 60 qualified leads per quarter.</p>
        <h3>3. SaaS — Email marketing hub</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company built an email marketing hub with a 6,000-word pillar page plus 22 supporting articles on deliverability, subject lines, segmentation, and automation. The hub captured position 1 for "email marketing guide" within 9 months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content hub vs traditional blog — which to use</h2>
        <p>Both publish articles. The organization is different — and it matters for SEO.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content hub</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Organized by topic, not date</li>
              <li>Deliberate internal linking around a pillar</li>
              <li>Builds topical authority fast</li>
              <li>Pillar page inherits authority from cluster</li>
              <li>Best for competitive SEO categories</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Traditional blog</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Organized chronologically</li>
              <li>Random internal links (or none)</li>
              <li>Each post competes on its own</li>
              <li>Authority does not compound across posts</li>
              <li>Best for news, updates, thought leadership</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 content hub best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Publish the pillar page first, but keep it flexible.</strong> Ship a v1 pillar, then update it as supporting articles reveal new angles.</li>
          <li><strong>Link with descriptive anchor text.</strong> Not "click here" — use the target keyword or exact subtopic name.</li>
          <li><strong>Target one intent per article.</strong> If two articles target the same intent you cannibalize both.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh the pillar quarterly.</strong> The pillar is the anchor. Stale pillars drag the whole cluster.</li>
          <li><strong>Track hub-level metrics, not just page-level.</strong> Combined traffic, average position, and internal link click-through tell the real story.</li>
          <li><strong>Externalize the hub in your navigation.</strong> Link to the pillar from your main nav or footer so readers can find it.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — publishing supporting articles without a pillar</div>
          <p>Supporting articles without a pillar to link back to become disconnected blog posts. Every hub needs the pillar page live before you scale supporting content — otherwise the internal linking structure never forms.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content hub mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Choosing a topic too narrow for 15+ articles.</strong> If you cannot brainstorm 20 subtopics, the hub is too small.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to link back to the pillar.</strong> Every supporting article needs a link to the pillar. Miss this and the cluster does not form.</li>
          <li><strong>Cannibalizing the pillar with a supporting article.</strong> Two pages targeting the same head-term compete instead of stacking.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring content decay.</strong> Old supporting articles drag the pillar. Refresh at 6-month intervals.</li>
          <li><strong>Building the hub in isolation from the rest of the site.</strong> Link from existing high-authority pages into the hub to speed up ranking.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps you build content hubs</h2>
        <p>theStacc maps your topic universe, produces the pillar page, and ships the 10 to 30 supporting articles as part of one managed workflow. Every article is briefed with internal-linking instructions so the cluster forms as it grows — no orphaned posts, no missed pillars.</p>

